    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Conscience, Discarded</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sandra Andickes letter, commenting on July 15 obituary of Holocaust historian Jan Karski, praises his principled heroism during World War II (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Jan Karski Dies at 86; Warned West About Holocaust'' (obituary, July 15), detailing his principled heroism, was inspiring. How painful it must have been for him, after repeatedly risking his life to gather information for Western leaders about the devastation of the Holocaust, to find that they had ''discarded their conscience.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Jan Karski Dies at 86; Warned West About Holocaust'' (obituary, July 15), detailing his principled heroism, was inspiring. How painful it must have been for him, after repeatedly risking his life to gather information for Western leaders about the devastation of the Holocaust, to find that they had ''discarded their conscience.''</p>
        <p>Sadly, Mr. Karski's obituary reminds us that Western leaders are still discarding their conscience, as evidenced by the failure to prevent or stop genocide in Rwanda.</p>
        <p>SANDRA ADICKES  Dayton, N.J., July 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
